To intercept network requests in the browser using JavaScript, you can use the `XMLHttpRequest` object or the `fetch` API. Here's an example using `XMLHttpRequest`:

```javascript
// Create a new XMLHttpRequest object
var xhr = new XMLHttpRequest();

// Set up a callback function to handle the response
xhr.onreadystatechange = function() {
  if (xhr.readyState === 4 && xhr.status === 200) {
    // Handle the successful response here
    console.log(xhr.responseText);
  }
};

// Open a new request and specify the URL
xhr.open('GET', 'https://example.com/api/data');

// Send the request
xhr.send();
```

This code creates a new `XMLHttpRequest` object, sets up a callback function to handle the response, opens a new request and specifies the URL, and finally sends the request. You can use similar code to intercept network requests made by the browser and handle their responses.

Alternatively, you can use the `fetch` API like this:

```javascript
// Send a fetch request
fetch('https://example.com/api/data')
  .then(response => response.json())
  .then(data => console.log(data))
  .catch(error => console.error(error));
```

This code sends a fetch request with the specified URL, then handles the response using the Promises syntax. This method is easier to use and is recommended for modern browsers that support it.
